\begin_layout Standard
A 
\emph on
probability space
\emph default
 is a mathematical abstraction specifying the necessary conditions for reasoning
 coherently about collections of uncertain events 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kolmogorov1950,544199,Griffiths2003,Grabisch2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Although they can be used to describe an individual quantum experiment,
 to describe a family of quantum experiments, we would like to glue their
 probability spaces together to define a quantum probability space.
 The glued quantum probability space is well-behaved since not only we can
 define the expectation values, but the quantum probability measure defined
 on the whole space can be simply induced by the Born rule according to
 Gleason's theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gleason1957,Redhead1987-REDINA,peres1995quantum,RichmanBridges1999,Hamhalter2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Classical Probability Space
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Classical-and-Quantum"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a finite sample space
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 representing all possible outcomes of a process, and its power set 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\Omega}$
\end_inset

 as the classical event space, a classical probability measure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 maps every event 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq\Omega$
\end_inset

 to a number 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(E\right)\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 specifying how likely one of the outcomes in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 will happen.
 To maintain the coherence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is subject to the following constraints: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\emptyset\right)=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\Omega\right)=1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\Omega\backslash E\right)=\mu\left(\overline{E}\right)=1-\mu\left(E\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\backslash E$
\end_inset

 is the complement of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, and we may simply write 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\backslash E$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{E}$
\end_inset

 if the sample space
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is clear from the context.
  Moreover, we require 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(E_{0}\cup E_{1}\right)=\mu\left(E_{0}\right)+\mu\left(E_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 for each pair of disjoint events 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}\subseteq\Omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}\subseteq\Omega$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the previous abstraction doesn't specify the process to generate the
 outcomes, this process could well be a quantum experiment.
 Let us prepare a beam of one kind of spin
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 particles, and split it by an inhomogeneous magnetic field along the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-axis as a well-known Stern-Gerlach type experiment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key ":/content/aip/journal/jmp/21/1/10.1063/1.524312,peres1995quantum,schwinger2001quantum"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This beam will be split into three beams, and we will call the outcome
 beams bent up as 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{0}$
\end_inset

, bent down as 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{1}$
\end_inset

, and not-bent as 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Instead of sending a beam of particles, if only one particle is sent to
 the beam splitter, we will only get one of the outcomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{1}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{2}$
\end_inset

, and there is a probability to get each outcome.
 In the language of our abstraction, the set of outcomes is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}=\{\ket{0},\ket{1},\ket{2}\}$
\end_inset

.
 All possible events are 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{0}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{1}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{0},\ket{1}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{0},\ket{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{1},\ket{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Each time we perform this experiment, it induces a classical probability
 measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{0}\colon2^{\Omega_{0}}\rightarrow\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, if we prepare the particles in the 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

``
\end_layout

\end_inset

same
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

''
\end_layout

\end_inset

 way as the particle inducing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{0}$
\end_inset

, they will induce the same classical probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One special feature of quantum experiments is that the probabilities in
 different experiments are correlated.
 Consider another experiment sending the 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

``
\end_layout

\end_inset

same
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

''
\end_layout

\end_inset

 particle as the previous one, but we rotate the inhomogeneous magnetic
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $90\textdegree$
\end_inset

 and now along the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis.
 This time we call the outcome beams bent left as 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\ps}$
\end_inset

, bent right as 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\ms}$
\end_inset

, and not-bent still as 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Although the sample space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}=\left\{ \ket{\ps},\ket{\ms},\ket{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and the probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}\colon2^{\Omega_{1}}\rightarrow\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 defined by this experiment is different from the previous one, they all
 produce a not-bent outcome
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ket{2}$
\end_inset

, and the probability of the common event 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is believed to be the same, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{0}\left(\left\{ \ket{2}\right\} \right)=\mu_{1}\left(\left\{ \ket{2}\right\} \right)\,.\label{eq:mu0-equal-mu1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we may rotate the inhomogeneous magnetic field any degree
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, it is nature to represent the two bent outcomes as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\theta\ket{0}+\cos\theta\ket{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta\ket{0}-\sin\theta\ket{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\ps}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\ms}$
\end_inset

 can be represented as 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\ps}=\frac{\ket{0}+\ket{1}}{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\ms}=\frac{\ket{0}-\ket{1}}{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Conventionally 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "peres1995quantum,schwinger2001quantum"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we will then postulate any normalized complex vector spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{1}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{2}$
\end_inset

 could be a measurement outcome, any orthonormal basis form a sample space,
 and sending a particle to this orthonormal basis inducing a classical probabili
ty measure.
 In general, as long as sending the same particle, the probability of the
 same event in different experiments should always be the same, i.e., giving
 two induced classical probability measures 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu'\colon2^{\Omega'}\rightarrow\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu''\colon2^{\Omega''}\rightarrow\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, the probabilities of getting 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq\Omega'\cap\Omega''$
\end_inset

 are the same
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu'\left(E\right)=\mu''\left(E\right)\,.\label{eq:mu-equal-same-event}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


